---
import MarketingNav from "../../components/MarketingNav.astro";
import MarketingFooter from "../../components/MarketingFooter.astro";
import MarketingLayout from "../../layouts/MarketingLayout.astro";
import { APP_WORKSPACE_URL } from "../../lib/urls";

---

<MarketingLayout
  title="What an ATS Score Measures | SyncResume"
  description="Understand what an ATS score can and cannot tell you, and how to use it while tailoring a resume to a job description."
  canonicalPath="/blog/what-ats-score-measures"
>
  <div class="landing">
    <MarketingNav />

    <article class="landing-section landing-article">
      <div class="landing-container">
        <p class="landing-eyebrow">ATS guides</p>
        <h1 class="landing-page-title">What does your ATS score actually measure?</h1>
        <p class="landing-page-lede">
          An ATS score is a matching signal, not a guarantee. It helps you see whether your resume speaks the language of a specific job description.
        </p>

        <div class="landing-article-body">
          <h2>The score is job-specific</h2>
          <p>
            A strong score for one role can be weak for another. The same resume may match a backend engineering role well and a product-focused role poorly because the required skills, tools, and responsibilities differ.
          </p>

          <h2>What usually affects the score</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Required skills and technologies from the job description.</li>
            <li>Repeated responsibilities such as migration, automation, stakeholder communication, or support.</li>
            <li>Seniority cues, domain language, and role-specific outcomes.</li>
            <li>Whether your strongest bullets contain the most important requirements.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>What the score does not measure</h2>
          <p>
            It does not know if you will interview well, whether a recruiter likes your background, or whether a requirement is truly mandatory. It is one input. Use it to find gaps, then keep the final resume accurate and readable.
          </p>

          <h2>How to use it well</h2>
          <p>
            Treat the score as a diagnostic. If it is low, add missing relevant terms only when they are true to your experience. If it is high but the resume sounds generic, improve the bullets so they show specific outcomes.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="landing-article-cta">
          <div>
            <h2>Get a before-and-after match score.</h2>
            <p>Run a resume against a target role and see what changes lift alignment.</p>
          </div>
          <a class="btn btn-primary" href={APP_WORKSPACE_URL}>Start tailoring free</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>


    <MarketingFooter />
  </div>
</MarketingLayout>
